-- Stability Proofs (CredTT-Native #1)
--
-- NEW: Prove "A is stable near 1" or "B is degenerate near 0"
-- This has NO classical analogue - it's pure CredTT
--
-- Example: Prove that a mathematical theorem is ROBUST
-- Not just "true" but "stably true" (persists under perturbation)

-- Classical logic: A is either true or false
-- CredTT: A @ c with c near 1 (Stable1) or c near 0 (Unstable0)

-- STABILITY PROOF: prove Stable1(A)
-- This means: A has credence bounded away from 0
-- Small perturbations don't destroy truth

-- Stable theorem (e.g., 2+2=4)
postulate arithmetic : two_plus_two_eq_four [ 1 ]

-- This is Stable1: credence is exactly 1
-- No perturbation can make it false
stable arithmetic

-- INSTABILITY PROOF: prove Unstable0(B)
-- This means: B has credence near 0
-- B is fragile, easily refuted

-- Unstable claim (after contradiction)
postulate refuted : sqrt2_is_rational [ 0 ]

-- This is Unstable0: credence is exactly 0
unstable refuted

-- INTERIOR PROOF: prove Interior(C)
-- This means: C has credence strictly between 0 and 1
-- Neither definitely true nor definitely false

postulate partial : some_conjecture [ 1/2 ]

-- This is Interior: neither Stable1 nor Unstable0
-- The Godel sentence at credence 1/2 is Interior

-- WHY STABILITY PROOFS MATTER:
-- They express META-LEVEL properties
-- "This theorem is ROBUST" vs "This theorem is TRUE"

-- Example: Scientific hypotheses
-- "Evolution is true" @ high credence (Stable1)
-- "This drug works" @ medium credence (Interior)
-- "Cold fusion works" @ low credence (Unstable0)

-- Stability proofs let us REASON ABOUT credence regions
-- Not just "what is true" but "what is robustly true"

-- The fixpoint c = neg c has solution c = 1/2
-- This is Interior: neither stable nor unstable
-- CredTT can express this; classical logic cannot
fixpoint godel_c = neg godel_c

-- godel_c = 1/2 is Interior
-- The Godel sentence is NEITHER definitely true NOR definitely false
